# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amazon-redshift
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] Amazon Redshift is based on an older version of PostgreSQL 8.0.2, and Redshift has made changes to that version.
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] An initial preview beta was released in November 2012 and a full release was made available on February 15, 2013.
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] Partner companies providing data integration tools include Informatica and SnapLogic.
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] System integration and consulting partners include Accenture, Deloitte, Capgemini and DXC Technology.
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] The "Red" in Redshift's name alludes to Oracle, a competing computer technology company sometimes informally referred to as "Big Red" due to its red corporate color.
[src:amazon-redshift/amazon-redshift] Hence, customers choosing to move their databases from Oracle to Redshift would be "shifting" from "Red".
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] This section explains the components that make up the Amazon Redshift data warehouse architecture, as shown in the following figure.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift integrates with various data loading and ETL (extract, transform, and load) tools and business intelligence (BI) reporting, data mining, and analytics tools.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift is based on open standard PostgreSQL, so most existing SQL client applications will work with only minimal changes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For information about important differences between Amazon Redshift SQL and PostgreSQL, see Amazon Redshift and PostgreSQL.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The core infrastructure component of an Amazon Redshift data warehouse is a *cluster*.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] A cluster is composed of one or more *compute nodes*.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] If a cluster is provisioned with two or more compute nodes, an additional *leader node* coordinates the compute nodes and handles external communication.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Your client application interacts directly only with the leader node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The compute nodes are transparent to external applications.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The leader node manages communications with client programs and all communication with compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] It parses and develops execution plans to carry out database operations, in particular, the series of steps necessary to obtain results for complex queries.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Based on the execution plan, the leader node compiles code, distributes the compiled code to the compute nodes, and assigns a portion of the data to each compute node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The leader node distributes SQL statements to the compute nodes only when a query references tables that are stored on the compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] All other queries run exclusively on the leader node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift is designed to implement certain SQL functions only on the leader node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] A query that uses any of these functions will return an error if it references tables that reside on the compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For more information, see SQL functions supported on the leader node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The leader node compiles code for individual elements of the execution plan and assigns the code to individual compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The compute nodes run the compiled code and send intermediate results back to the leader node for final aggregation.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Each compute node has its own dedicated CPU and memory, which are determined by the node type.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] As your workload grows, you can increase the compute capacity of a cluster by increasing the number of nodes, upgrading the node type, or both.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift provides several node types for your compute needs.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For details of each node type, see Amazon Redshift clusters in the *Amazon Redshift Management Guide*.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Data warehouse data is stored in a separate storage tier Redshift Managed Storage (RMS).
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] RMS provides the ability to scale your storage to petabytes using Amazon S3 storage.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] RMS lets you scale and pay for computing and storage independently, so that you can size your cluster based only on your computing needs.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] It automatically uses high-performance SSD-based local storage as tier-1 cache.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] It also takes advantage of optimizations, such as data block temperature, data block age, and workload patterns to deliver high performance while scaling storage automatically to Amazon S3 when needed without requiring any action.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] A compute node is partitioned into slices.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Each slice is allocated a portion of the node's memory and disk space, where it processes a portion of the workload assigned to the node.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The leader node manages distributing data to the slices and apportions the workload for any queries or other database operations to the slices.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The slices then work in parallel to complete the operation.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The number of slices per node is determined by the node size of the cluster.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For more information about the number of slices for each node size, go to About clusters and nodes in the *Amazon Redshift Management Guide*.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] When you create a table, you can optionally specify one column as the distribution key.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] When the table is loaded with data, the rows are distributed to the node slices according to the distribution key that is defined for a table.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Choosing a good distribution key enables Amazon Redshift to use parallel processing to load data and run queries efficiently.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For information about choosing a distribution key, see Choose the best distribution style.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift takes advantage of high-bandwidth connections, close proximity, and custom communication protocols to provide private, very high-speed network communication between the leader node and compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] The compute nodes run on a separate, isolated network that client applications never access directly.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] A cluster contains one or more databases.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] User data is stored on the compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Your SQL client communicates with the leader node, which in turn coordinates query run with the compute nodes.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift is a relational database management system (RDBMS), so it is compatible with other RDBMS applications.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Although it provides the same functionality as a typical RDBMS, including online transaction processing (OLTP) functions such as inserting and deleting data, Amazon Redshift is optimized for high-performance analysis and reporting of very large datasets.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] Amazon Redshift and PostgreSQL have a number of very important differences that you need to take into account as you design and develop your data warehouse applications.
[src:amazon-redshift/c-high-level-system-architecture] For information about how Amazon Redshift SQL differs from PostgreSQL, see Amazon Redshift and PostgreSQL.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:amazon-redshift/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:amazon-redshift/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] One approach is grid computing, where the processing power of many computers in distributed, diverse administrative domains is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] An example is BOINC, a volunteer-based, opportunistic grid system, whereby the grid provides power only on a best effort basis.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] Another approach is grouping many processors in close proximity to each other, as in a computer cluster.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] In such a centralized system the speed and flexibility of the interconnect becomes very important, and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced InfiniBand systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] The term also applies to massively parallel processor arrays (MPPAs), a type of integrated circuit with an array of hundreds or thousands of central processing units (CPUs) and random-access memory (RAM) banks.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] These processors pass work to one another through a reconfigurable interconnect of channels.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] By harnessing many processors working in parallel, an MPPA chip can accomplish more demanding tasks than conventional chips.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] MPPAs are based on a software parallel programming model for developing high-performance embedded system applications.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] Goodyear MPP was an early implementation of a massively parallel computer architecture.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] MPP architectures are the second most common supercomputer implementations after clusters, as of November 2013.
[src:amazon-redshift/massively-parallel-processing] Data warehouse appliances such as Teradata, Netezza or Microsoft's PDW commonly implement an MPP architecture to handle the processing of very large amounts of data in parallel.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Welcome to the *Amazon Redshift Database Developer Guide*.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] This guide focuses on helping you understand how to use Amazon Redshift to create and manage a data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] If you work with databases as a designer, software developer, or administrator, this guide gives you the information you need to design, build, query, and maintain your data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Amazon Redshift is a fully managed, petabyte-scale data warehouse service in the cloud.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Amazon Redshift Serverless lets you access and analyze data without the usual configurations of a provisioned data warehouse.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Resources are automatically provisioned and data warehouse capacity is intelligently scaled to deliver fast performance for even the most demanding and unpredictable workloads.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] You don't incur charges when the data warehouse is idle, so you only pay for what you use.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Regardless of the size of the dataset, you can load data and start querying right away in the Amazon Redshift query editor v2 or in your favorite business intelligence (BI) tool.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Enjoy the best price performance and familiar SQL features in an easy-to-use, zero administration environment.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] This topic describes prerequisites you need to use Amazon Redshift.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] Before you use this guide, you should read Get started with Redshift Serverless data warehouses, which goes over how to complete the following tasks.
[src:amazon-redshift/welcome] You should also know how to use your SQL client and should have a fundamental understanding of the SQL language.
